                "id": "gui.tutorials.html_css_intro.boilerplate",
                "default": "Your workspace already has the html, head, and body blocks — every webpage starts that way (you built this in the Hello Web tutorial). Today we just focus on what we add INSIDE the body."
            }
        },
        {
            "title": "Structure and Style — Two Jobs",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlCssIntroStructureVsStyle.webp",
            "imageFocus": {"x": 50, "y": 50, "zoom": 1},
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.structureVsStyle",
                "default": "Until now you have learned HTML — the STRUCTURE of a page (head, body, headings, paragraphs, lists). Today you start learning CSS — the STYLE (colours, sizes, spacing, fonts). HTML decides what is there. CSS decides how it looks. Two jobs. Same page."
            }
        },
        {
            "title": "Add a Heading to Style",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlCssIntroHeading.webp",
            "imageFocus": {
                "x": 55,
                "y": 50,
                "zoom": 1.4
            },
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.heading",
                "default": "Drag a heading inside the body. Keep level 1 and type Hello CSS. We'll change its colours next."
            },
            "highlightBlock": {
                "category": "html5",
                "blockType": "html5_html5_heading"
            }
        },
        {
            "title": "Add a Style Block",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlCssIntroStyle.webp",
            "imageFocus": {
                "x": 55,
                "y": 50,
                "zoom": 1.4
            },
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.style",
                "default": "Drag the style block inside the head. The style block is where all your CSS rules live."
            },
            "highlightBlock": {
                "category": "html5",
                "blockType": "html5_html5_style"
            },
            "validate": true
        },
        {
            "title": "Pick the Heading with a Selector",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlCssIntroSelector.webp",
            "imageFocus": {"x": 50, "y": 50, "zoom": 1.4},
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.selector",
                "default": "Drag a selector block inside the style. Click the selector field and replace the text with h1. The selector tells CSS which elements to change."
            },
            "highlightBlock": {
                "category": "css",
                "blockType": "css_css_selector"
            }
        },
        {
            "title": "Selector Picks the Element",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlCssIntroSelectorPicks.webp",
            "imageFocus": {"x": 50, "y": 50, "zoom": 1},
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.selectorPicks",
                "default": "A CSS selector is a pointer. h1 means EVERY h1 on the page. p means EVERY paragraph. The styles inside the curly braces apply to every element the selector picks."
            }
        },
        {
            "title": "Set the Text Colour",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlCssIntroColor.webp",
            "imageFocus": {
                "x": 55,
                "y": 50,
                "zoom": 1.4
            },
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.color",
                "default": "Drag a color block inside the selector. Replace red with darkblue. This sets the text colour of every h1 on the page."
            },
            "highlightBlock": {
                "category": "css",
                "blockType": "css_css_color"
            }
        },
        {
            "title": "Set the Background Colour",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlCssIntroBg.webp",
            "imageFocus": {
                "x": 55,
                "y": 50,
                "zoom": 1.4
            },
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.bg",
                "default": "Drag a background-color block below the color block, still inside the selector. Replace skyblue with lightyellow. This is the box behind the text."
            },
            "highlightBlock": {
                "category": "css",
                "blockType": "css_css_background_color"
            }
        },
        {
            "title": "See Your First Style",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlCssIntroView.webp",
            "imageFocus": {
                "x": 75,
                "y": 50,
                "zoom": 1.3
            },
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.viewTab",
                "default": "Click the View tab. Is your heading dark blue on a light yellow background?"
            },
            "highlightUI": "viewTab"
        },
        {
            "title": "HTML Describes, Python Does",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlIntro_markupVsProgramming.webp",
            "imageFocus": {"x": 50, "y": 50, "zoom": 1},
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.markupVsProgramming",
                "default": "Quick comparison. HTML is what we call a MARKUP language — it DESCRIBES things on the page (this is a heading, this is a paragraph, this is a list). It can't ask the user a question. It can't add 2 plus 2. It just lays out what's there. CSS is similar — it describes how things LOOK. Python is different — Python is a PROGRAMMING language. Python can DO things — ask the user, decide, repeat, calculate. Three different jobs working together: HTML structures the page, CSS styles it, and Python or JavaScript can make it move and respond."
            }
        },
        {
            "title": "How CSS Works",
            "image": "/static/tutorials/steps/htmlCssIntroRecap.webp",
            "imageFocus": {
                "x": 75,
                "y": 50,
                "zoom": 1.3
            },
            "narration": {
                "id": "gui.tutorials.htmlCssIntro.recap",
                "default": "CSS has two parts: a selector that picks elements, and properties that change how they look. Color sets the text. Background-color sets the box behind it."
            }
        }
    ]
}
